   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604742_unknown_page01.jpg"/>
            <p>new, and perfectly true idea - and in<lb/>
               this age of repetition <add>&amp; deception</add>, a perfectly new &amp;<lb/>
               perfectly true idea is so rare that it is <choice><orig>suffi<lb/>
                  cient</orig><reg>sufficient</reg></choice> to make a reputation - <del>The</del><lb/></p>
               <p>I allude to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ConsB1">M. B. Constant</persName>s remark<lb/>
               that despotism has produced in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#FR">France</placeName><lb/>
               a power which has become more than<lb/>
               a match for itself - It has produced<lb/>
               that system of industry which render<lb/>
               men independant of court favor &amp;<lb/>
               which creates that <hi rend="underline">substantive</hi> body of<lb/>
               public opinion which can stand alone<lb/></p>
               <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#ConsB1">M. Constant</persName> might much improve<lb/>
               himself as a speaker &amp; a writer by studying<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BurkE1">Burke</persName> whom he more resembles in<lb/>
               manner than any of our speakers o<gap></gap><lb/>
               writers - <del>But</del> he wants more of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BurkE1">Burke</persName><gap></gap><lb/>
               strength and has too much of his <unclear>ornament</unclear> <gap></gap><lb/>
               - too much declamation - too many words - 10 times <gap></gap><lb/></p>
               <p>You oblige me much by sending <unclear></unclear><lb/>
               me these tracts which keep me up with<lb/>
               the current of your literature &amp; politics<lb/>
                  For The 2 numbers of your <title ref="./Workography.xml#Revue1">Revue - <choice><orig>Encyclo-<lb/>
                  pedique</orig><reg>Encyclopedique</reg></choice></title> which <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ParkE1">Madame Belloc</persName> tells me<lb/>
               you have sent to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeleX1">M Deleports</persName> for me to<lb/>
               come over with her next parcel I thank<lb/>
               you sincerely - My brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd <choice><orig>Edge-<lb/>
                  worth</orig><reg>Edgeworth</reg></choice></persName> intends to set out from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> for<lb/>
               England in a few days &amp; will bring the<lb/>
               books to me - He will call out <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeleX1">M Deleport</persName>s<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Harvard_604742_unknown_page02.jpg,"/>
            <p>With a just sense of your continued<reg></reg>
               attentions to me</p>             <closer>I am<lb/>
                  <choice><orig>D<hi rend= "superscript">r</hi>.</orig><reg>Dear</reg></choice> Sir<lb/>
                  Your obliged &amp; grateful<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
               </closer>
            <closer>
               <address>
                  <addrLine>a</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Monsieur</addrLine>
                  <addrLine><persName ref="./Personography.xml#JullM1">Mons<hi rend= "superscript">r</hi>. Jullien</persName></addrLine>
                  <addrLine><placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#18-Rue-d'Enfen-Saint-Michel_FR">Rue d'Enfen Saint-Michel, N<hi rend= "superscript">o</hi>. 18</placeName></addrLine>
               </address>               
            </closer>
